\begin_layout Standard
The analysis of diffractive effects can be separated into two regimes: Fresnel
 (or near field) diffraction and Fraunhofer (or far field) diffraction.
 In general, an electromagnetic wave that is radiated by a point source
 has a non-zero curvature that decreases in a manner directly proportional
 to the square of the propagated distance.
 Near field diffraction occurs when the diffractive object or aperture is
 close enough to the source, and the observer is close enough to the aperture,
 that the curvature of the incident wave cannot be neglected for the purposes
 of describing the resulting diffraction pattern.
 In the Fraunhofer limit, on the other hand, the distances between the source
 and the aperture and the aperture and the observer are sufficiently large
 such that it is possible to treat the waves incident on the aperture and
 the observer as plane waves.
 More quantitatively, if 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 is the size of the aperture or obstacle, 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 is the wavelength of the radiation, and 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is the smallest of either the source-aperture distance or the aperture-observer
 distance, then the Fraunhofer approximation applies when 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
R>\frac{b^{2}}{\lambda}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The first experiment of this project compares expected Fraunhofer diffraction
 patterns of different apertures and obtacles to ones obtained in the laboratory.
 We will not derive the pattern for each of the apertures; suffice is to
 say that they can be obtained by solving the Kirchoff diffraction integral
 in the Fraunhofer limit.
 This integral describes the electric field 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 at the observer's position 
\begin_inset Formula $(Y,Z)$
\end_inset

, and is given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
E(Y,Z)=\iintop_{-\infty}^{\infty}\mathcal{A}(y,z)\exp\left[\frac{\imath k(Yy+Zz)}{R}\right]dxdy
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 are the coordinates in a point at the aperture, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{A}=\mathcal{A}_{0}(y,z)e^{\imath\phi(y,z)}$
\end_inset

 is known as the aperture function, which describes the amplitude of the
 field over the aperture.
 The function 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(y,z)$
\end_inset

 describes the variation of the phase in the 
\begin_inset Formula $yz$
\end_inset

 plane, and 
\begin_inset Formula $k=\frac{2\pi}{\lambda}$
\end_inset

 is the wavenumber.
 An illustration of the geometry can be found in Figure 1.
 The limits of the integral in (2) are from 
\begin_inset Formula $-\infty$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\infty$
\end_inset

, because the aperture function can be regarded to be zero everywhere except
 at the region that corresponds to the aperture.
 Evaluation of this integral for an appropriate choice of aperture function
 allows us to find the far field irradiance pattern of a particular kind
 of aperture.
 A more detailed analysis can be found in chapter 11 of [3], and chapters
 VIII and XI of [4].
\end_layout

