\begin_layout Subsection
Diffraction grating maxima
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Diffraction gratings are essentially a multiple slits aperture with large
 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 and small separation 
\begin_inset Formula $b>a$
\end_inset

.
 The transmission diffraction grating, in fact, is just that.
 It is possible to determine the wavelength of the light that passes through
 a diffraction grating in a simple way, by measuring the distance between
 the positions of the maxima at a screen.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{m}$
\end_inset

 be the separation between the zeroth order maximum and the maxima of order
 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

 be the distance from the diffraction grating to the screen, and the wavelength
 of the light will be given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\lambda=\frac{bs_{m}}{m\sqrt{s_{m}^{2}+m^{2}d^{2}}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

This is known as the grating formula.
 A complete derivation can be found in chapter 10 of [3].
 We will make use of this equation in experiment 2 in order to calculate
 the wavelength of the laser light.
\end_layout

